ariants":[{"name":"Weber","meanings":["German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): occupational name for a weaver, Middle High German <i>wëber</i>, German <i>Weber</i>, an agent derivative of <i>weben</i> ‘to weave’. This form of the surname is also established in many other parts of Europe, notably in France (mainly Alsace and Lorraine), Poland, and the Netherlands. In Hungary it is mostly spelled <b>Wéber</b> and <b>Véber</b>. In Russia, Slovenia, Czechia, Slovakia, and Croatia it is (also) established in the Slavicized form   Veber  , which is in Czechia also spelled <b>Vebr</b>. Compare   Waber  ,   Weaber  ,   Weaver  ,   Webber  , and   Webre  .","History: As a name of ultimately Swiss German origin the surname <i>Weber</i> is also established among the American Mennonites. However, descendants of the early Mennonite settlers, who came to PA in the early 18th century, mostly bear the Americanized form of the name (see   Weaver  )."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":32,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705197,"age":105,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Weaver was born about 1350, in Herefordshire, England, his father, Walter Weaver II, was 17 and his mother, Lady Joane Bohun, was 17. He married Margaret de Wysham about 1380, in Shropshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1350–":"umbes 1350–Surnud","1350–Male":"1350–Surnud","1350–1388":"1350–1388","1388–1413":"1388–1413","1334–1387":"1334–1387","1335–1375":"1335–1375","1413":"1413","about 1380":"umbes 1380","1335":"1335","1455":"1455","1334":"1334","1388":"1388","1387":"1387","1375":"1375","1350":"1350","about 1388":"umbes 1388","1382":"1382","about 1350":"umbes 1350","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Presteigh, Radnorshire, Wales":"Presteigne, Radnorshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1350–":"noin 1350–Kuollut","1350–Male":"1350–Kuollut","1350–1388":"1350–1388","1388–1413":"1388–1413","1334–1387":"1334–1387","1335–1375":"1335–1375","1413":"1413","about 1380":"noin 1380","1335":"1335","1455":"1455","1334":"1334","1388":"1388","1387":"1387","1375":"1375","1350":"1350","about 1388":"noin 1388","1382":"1382","about 1350":"noin 1350","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Presteigh, Radnorshire, Wales":"Presteigne, Radnorshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"